.TH MX-CLEANUP 1 "July 2026" "mx-cleanup 26.07.3" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
mx-cleanup \- GUI for disk cleanup and system maintenance on MX Linux
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B mx-cleanup
.RI [ options ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B mx-cleanup
is a graphical application that offers several easy actions to check
and increase hard drive space. It can safely remove old and unnecessary
files and clear logs through a user-friendly interface.
.PP
Available cleanup categories include:
.TP
.B Folders
User cache and thumbnail cache.
.TP
.B Apt (Installation)
Package cache cleanup and purging of residual configuration left behind
by removed packages. "Old files" removes package archives that can no
longer be downloaded again; "All files" empties the cache completely.
.TP
.B Logs
System logs under
.IR /var/log .
"Old logs" removes rotated logs ending in
.IR .gz ", " .old ", and " .1 ;
"All logs" truncates every log file to empty instead.
.TP
.B Trash
The desktop trash can, for the selected user or for all users.
.TP
.B Flatpak
Unused Flatpak runtimes.
.PP
Cleanup can be run once immediately, or scheduled to run automatically
daily, weekly, monthly, or at every reboot, via
.BR cron (8).
.PP
Actions that require administrator privileges are carried out by a
separate, verb-based privileged helper, invoked through
.BR pkexec (1).
.B mx-cleanup
itself must be started as a normal (non-root) user; it refuses to run
when invoked as root.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Display help on command line options and exit.
.TP
.B \-\-help\-all
Display help on command line options, including generic Qt/QPA options
such as
.BR \-\-platform ", " \-\-session ", and " \-\-reverse ,
and exit.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-version
Display version information and exit.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.config/MX-Linux/mx-cleanup.conf
Per-user preferences (cache/thumbnail cleanup, flatpak, trash).
.TP
.I /usr/bin/mx-cleanup-script
Generated cron/@reboot script for a user's own scheduled cleanup.
.TP
.I /usr/bin/mx-cleanup-system-script
Shared, system-wide script (package cache, purge, logs, all-users trash)
invoked by every user's scheduled cleanup script.
.TP
.I /etc/cron.daily/mx-cleanup
.TQ
.I /etc/cron.weekly/mx-cleanup
.TQ
.I /etc/cron.monthly/mx-cleanup
.TQ
.I /etc/cron.d/mx-cleanup
Cron entries installed for the selected schedule.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR baobab (1),
.BR pkexec (1),
.BR cron (8)
